                Senate
              </span> <span style="text-transform: uppercase">March 23, 2026</span><br/></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 1214</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Ochoa Bogh<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 19, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to add<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> and repeal</i></font> Section 424.4<font color="#B30000"><strike> to</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> of</i></font> the Government Code, relating to state government. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SB 1214, as amended, Ochoa Bogh.
                          <font color="#B30000"><strike>State Butterfly. </strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>California State Library: study: state butterfly.</i></font></span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes various official emblems of the state, including establishing the California dog-face butterfly (zerene eurydice) as the official State Insect.<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Existing law establishes the California State Library within the state government and vests control of the library to the State Librarian. Existing law authorizes the California State Library to serve as the central reference and research library for the departments of state government and maintain adequate legislative reference and research library services for the Legislature.</i></font></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>This bill would establish the western monarch butterfly (danaus plexippus) as the official State Butterfly. The bill would make related findings and declarations.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the California State Library to research, in consultation with the public, on the best candidate for the official State Butterfly. The bill would require the California State Library, on or before January 1, 2028, to submit a report to the Legislature with the California State Library’s recommendations based on the study, as provided. The bill would repeal these provisions on January 1, 2032.</div></i></font></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase"><font color="#B30000"><strike>NO</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>YES</i></font></span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.17969856182417676"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SECTION 1.</i></font></h3> <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Section 424.4 is added to the Government Code, to read:</i></font></div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i></i></font><div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div id="id_ECD0B2DB-7862-4648-845C-2C8CC3BCABF2"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">424.4.</h6> (a) The California State Library shall conduct a study, in consultation with the public, on the best candidate for the official State Butterfly.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) On or before January 1, 2028, the California State Library shall submit a report to the Legislature with the California State Library’s recommendations based on the study conducted pursuant to subdivision (a).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report to be submitted pursuant to paragraph (1) shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) This section shall be repealed on January 1, 2032, pursuant to Section 10231.5.</div></p></div></div></i></font></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_0DC71598-C13E-4385-A8AF-CAEEDEADC48B"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>The western monarch butterfly is found throughout California and is easily recognized by its distinctive orange, black, and white wing pattern.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>The western monarch butterfly migrates more than 1,000 miles from the Rocky Mountain region to coastal California, where they overwinter at sites ranging from the County of Mendocino to Baja California from approximately October through February.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(c)<span class="EnSpace"/>During migration, western monarch populations have historically
				numbered between 20,000 and 200,000 butterflies along the California coast.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(d)<span class="EnSpace"/>During fall migration, monarch butterflies can be found in southern California desert regions, including the Coachella Valley, where they arrive in late September through early October to feed on the native milkweed species, including the evergreen rush milkweed.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(e)<span class="EnSpace"/>Butterflies play a vital ecological role as pollinators across California’s diverse ecosystems.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:BillSection><caml:BillSection id="id_0896DD97-1ECC-41AD-BC8D-31050BBD7783"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SEC. 2.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_ADDED" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:GOV:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2F%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'424.4'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION" xlink:type="locator">Section 424.4 is added to the <caml:DocName>Government Code</caml:DocName>, to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_47755FD0-9665-480F-905F-2B796B6C3948"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>424.4.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_8B343A3A-6F01-4039-8A52-D044DDC8FF92"><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>The western monarch butterfly (danaus plexippus) is the official State Butterfly.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection></strike></font></div></div></body></html>
